<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Medicare & IRMAA FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Learn how to reduce your Medicare costs with smart planning.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Ask About IRMAA</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is IRMAA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>IRMAA (Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount) is a surcharge added to Medicare Part B and Part D premiums for higher-income beneficiaries. The surcharge is based on your Modified Adjusted Gross Income from two years prior and can add over $1,000/month per person to your Medicare costs.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What are the 2025 IRMAA thresholds? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>For 2025, single filers with income over $103,000 (married filing jointly over $206,000) will pay IRMAA surcharges. The surcharges increase at multiple income tiers, with the highest tier kicking in at $500,000 for singles and $750,000 for married couples. We help you stay below the first threshold to avoid thousands in extra premiums.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I avoid IRMAA if I'm already paying it? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes, with forward planning. IRMAA is based on income from two years ago, so we manage your income today to avoid surcharges two years from now. We also review potential life-changing event appeals if your income has decreased due to retirement, death of a spouse, or other qualifying events.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How does IRMAA affect my Medicare Part D prescription drug coverage? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>IRMAA surcharges apply to both Medicare Part B (medical insurance) and Part D (prescription drug coverage). Higher-income beneficiaries pay an additional monthly amount on top of their Part D premium. Strategic income planning can help you avoid these surcharges entirely and significantly reduce your total Medicare costs.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I start planning for IRMAA? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Ideally, you should start IRMAA planning 3-5 years before Medicare enrollment at age 65. Because IRMAA is based on income from two years prior, early planning allows you to strategically manage Roth conversions, withdrawal sequencing, and other income decisions to minimize future Medicare surcharges. Even if you're already on Medicare, it's never too late to implement strategies that will reduce costs in future years.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What is IRMAA and why does it affect my Medicare costs? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>IRMAA is a surcharge added to your Medicare Part B and Part D premiums if your income exceeds certain thresholds. It is based on your Modified Adjusted Gross Income from two years prior. For 2026, the first IRMAA tier begins at $109,000 for single filers and $218,000 for married filing jointly. Exceeding these thresholds can add hundreds of dollars per month to your Medicare premiums.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Can I appeal IRMAA if my income has dropped? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Yes. If you have experienced a life-changing event such as retirement, reduction in work hours, death of a spouse, divorce, or loss of income-producing property, you can file Form SSA-44 with the Social Security Administration to request a reduction or elimination of your IRMAA surcharge based on your current (lower) income rather than the income from two years ago.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

